SIMPLE: ordination
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ordination
<hw>Or`di*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ordinatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>ordination</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of ordaining, appointing, or setting apart; the state of
being ordained, appointed, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The holy and wise <qex>ordination</qex> of God.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Virtue and vice have a natural <qex>ordination</qex> to the
happiness and misery of life respectively.</q>
<rj><qau>Norris.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The act of setting apart to an
office in the Christian ministry; the conferring of holy
orders.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Disposition; arrangement; order.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Angle of ordination</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the
angle between the axes of coordinates.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinative</ent>⟦br⟧
